# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bayesian-inference
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem is named after Thomas Bayes, a minister, statistician, and philosopher.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Bayes used conditional probability to provide an algorithm (his Proposition 9) that uses evidence to calculate limits on an unknown parameter.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] His work was published in 1763 as *An Essay Towards Solving a Problem in the Doctrine of Chances*.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Bayes studied how to compute a distribution for the probability parameter of a binomial distribution (in modern terminology).
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] After Bayes's death, his family gave his papers to a friend, the minister, philosopher, and mathematician Richard Price.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Price significantly edited the unpublished manuscript for two years before sending it to a friend who read it aloud at the Royal Society on 23 December 1763.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Price edited Bayes's major work "An Essay Towards Solving a Problem in the Doctrine of Chances" (1763), which appeared in *Philosophical Transactions*, and contains Bayes' theorem.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Price wrote an introduction to the paper that provides some of the philosophical basis of Bayesian statistics and chose one of the two solutions Bayes offered.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] In 1765, Price was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society in recognition of his work on Bayes's legacy.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] On 27 April, a letter sent to his friend Benjamin Franklin was read out at the Royal Society, and later published, in which Price applies this work to population and computing 'life-annuities'.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Independently of Bayes, Pierre-Simon Laplace used conditional probability to formulate the relation of an updated posterior probability from a prior probability, given evidence.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] He reproduced and extended Bayes's results in 1774, apparently unaware of Bayes's work, and summarized his results in *Théorie analytique des probabilités* (1812).
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] The Bayesian interpretation of probability was developed mainly by Laplace.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] About 200 years later, Sir Harold Jeffreys put Bayes's algorithm and Laplace's formulation on an axiomatic basis, writing in a 1973 book that Bayes' theorem "is to the theory of probability what the Pythagorean theorem is to geometry".
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Stephen Stigler used a Bayesian argument to conclude that Bayes' theorem was discovered by Nicholas Saunderson, a blind English mathematician, some time before Bayes, but that is disputed.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Thomas Bruss reviewed Bayes's "An essay towards solving a problem in the doctrine of chances" as communicated by Price.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] He agreed with Stigler's analysis on many points, but not on the question of priority.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Bruss underlined the intuitive part of Bayes's formula and added independent arguments about Bayes's probable motivation for his work.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] He concluded that, unless the contrary is proven, the name "Bayes' Theorem" or "Bayes' formula" is justifiable.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] The "Bayes factor" or "likelihood" that appears when writing Bayes' theorem in odds form appears in the early 1940s work of Alan Turing, who called it the "factor in favour of a proposition".
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] In 1878, Charles Sanders Peirce used the logarithm of this factor as the "weight of evidence" for a proposition.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] where A and B are events and $P(B)\neq 0$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem may be derived from the relation between joint and conditional probabilities.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] The events A and not- A , written $\neg A$ , are a mutually exclusive and exhaustive pair.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Suppose that a doctor is testing a patient for the presence of a certain disease.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] The patient either has the disease or does not; the test returns either positive or negative.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Let E be the event that the patient has the disease. $P(E)$ is the probability that the patient has the disease.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Let F be the event that the patient tests positive.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] The probability that the patient has the disease given that they test positive is thus denoted $P(E|F)$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] For example, if all patients with pancreatic cancer have certain symptoms, it does not follow that anyone who has those symptoms has pancreatic cancer.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Assuming the incidence rate of pancreatic cancer is 1/100000, while 10/99999 healthy people have the symptoms, the probability that a person who has the symptoms has pancreatic cancer is 9.1%.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Based on incidence rate, the following table presents the corresponding numbers per 100,000 people.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Suppose a particular test for whether someone has been using a drug (e.g., Substance D) is 99% sensitive, meaning the true positive rate (TPR) = 0.99.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] The test then has 99% true positive results (correct identification of drug use) for drug users.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] The test is also 99% specific, meaning its true negative rate (TNR) = 0.99.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Therefore, the test correctly identifies 99% of non-use for non-users, but also generates 1% false positives, or false positive rate (FPR) = 0.01, for non-users.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] An urn contains coins of three different types: A, B, and C.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Coins of type A are fair and, when flipped, come up heads with probability 0.5.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Coins of type B are biased and have probability 0.6 of turning up heads, and type-C coins come up heads with probability 0.9.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] The urn contains 2 type-A coins, 2 type-B coins and 1 type-C coin.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] A coin is drawn at random from the urn and flipped.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem gives the probability of a coin being of a given type given that it comes up heads: $P(A|H)={\frac {P(H|A)P(A)}{P(H)}},$ and likewise for $P(B|H)$ and $P(C|H)$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] The denominator can be found via the law of total probability: $P(H)=P(H|A)P(A)+P(H|B)P(B)+P(H|C)P(C).$ Assuming the coins are drawn from the urn at random, $P(A)=2/5$ , $P(B)=2/5$ , and $P(C)=1/5$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] The interpretation of Bayes' rule depends on the interpretation of probability ascribed to the terms.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] The two predominant classes of interpretation are described below.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] In Bayesian (or epistemological) interpretations, probability measures a rational "degree of belief".
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem links the degree of belief in a proposition before and after rationally accounting for evidence.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] For example, in a medical testing scenario, if a patient tests positive for a disease, the doctor will find it more plausible that the patient has that disease.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] For more on the application of Bayes' theorem under Bayesian interpretations of probability, see Bayesian inference.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] In the frequentist interpretations, probability measures a "proportion of outcomes".
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] For example, suppose an experiment is performed many times.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] *P*(*A*) is the proportion of outcomes with property *A* (the prior) and *P*(*B*) is the proportion with property *B*.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] *P*(*B*|*A*) is the proportion of outcomes with property *B* *out of* outcomes with property *A*, and *P*(*A*|*B*) is the proportion of those with *A* *out of* those with *B* (the posterior).
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] In many applications, for instance in Bayesian inference, the event *B* is fixed in the discussion and we wish to consider the effect of its having been observed on our belief in various possible events *A*.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] In such situations the denominator of the last expression, the probability of the given evidence *B*, is fixed; what we want to vary is *A*.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] In other words, the posterior is proportional to the prior times the likelihood.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] This holds for values x and y within the support of *X* and *Y*, ensuring $f_{X}(x)>0$ and $f_{Y}(y)>0$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Let $P_{Y}^{x}$ be the conditional distribution of Y given $X=x$ and let $P_{X}$ be the distribution of X .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Existence and uniqueness of the needed conditional expectation is a consequence of the Radon–Nikodym theorem.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Andrey Kolmogorov formulated this in 1933.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] He underlined the importance of conditional probability, writing, "I wish to call attention to ... the theory of conditional probabilities and conditional expectations".
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem determines the posterior distribution from the prior distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Uniqueness requires continuity assumptions.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem can be generalized to include improper prior distributions such as the uniform distribution on the real line.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Modern Markov chain Monte Carlo methods have boosted the importance of Bayes' theorem, including in cases with improper priors.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Probabilities are sometimes specified in terms of odds.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] For any proposition A , the ratio of the probability that A is true to the probability that A is false is called the odds on A .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem can be written using odds as follows.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] In symbols: $O(A|B)=O(A){\frac {P(B|A)}{P(B|\neg A)}}.$ This is often summarized by saying that the *posterior odds* are the *prior odds* times the likelihood.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] For example, suppose that a disease has a prevalence of 1%, i.e., the probability that a randomly chosen person is infected is 0.01.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] And suppose that a test for the disease returns the correct result with 99% probability.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] The desired result is obtained by identifying both expressions and solving for $P(A\vert B\cap C)$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] In subjective interpretations of probability theory, an event's probability is regarded as an agent's belief that the event will happen.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem is widely invoked to justify how an agent should update or modify their beliefs after receiving new information.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] If an agent assigns the probability $P(A)$ to the event A , $P(B)$ to the event B , and $P(B|A)$ to the event " B happens assuming A has already happened", Bayes' theorem gives the value of $P(A|B)$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Suppose that, after the agent has made these probability assignments, event B occurs.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] An agent who follows *Bayesian updating,* also known as updating by *conditionalization,* will change their probability for event A from the old value $P(A)$ to the new value $P'(A)=P(A|B)$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Conditionalization is not the only updating rule that might be considered rational.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] The issue of which assumptions can be invoked to constrain updating rules remains somewhat controversial.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] In quantum mechanics, probability distributions are generalized to density matrices, arrays of complex numbers that describe the preparation of a quantum system.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] A *quantum Bayes rule* can be formulated that expresses how density matrices are updated as new experimental data about a system is obtained.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] In Bayesian statistics, an object or system is represented by a mathematical model that contains one or more numerical parameters.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] The available information about the system is used to write a probability distribution over the possible values of those parameters, indicating which values are more plausible than others.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem is then used to update that probability distribution as new evidence is obtained.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Bayes' rule and computing conditional probabilities provide a method to solve a number of popular puzzles, such as the Three Prisoners problem, the Monty Hall problem, the Boy or Girl paradox, and the two envelopes problem.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Alan Turing and his collaborators at Bletchley Park pioneered the use of Bayes' theorem for breaking ciphers during World War II.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] In 1941, Turing wrote a set of pedagogical notes introducing Bayesian methods of cryptanalysis by applying them to problems like solving a Vigenère cipher, which were simpler than his team's primary focus, reading messages encrypted by the Enigma machine.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem was also applied to the cracking of the Japanese naval code JN 25.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] In genetics, Bayes' rule can be used to estimate the probability that someone has a specific genotype.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Many people seek to assess their chances of being affected by a genetic disease or their likelihood of being a carrier for a recessive gene of interest.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] A Bayesian analysis can be done based on family history or genetic testing to predict whether someone will develop a disease or pass one on to their children.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem is employed in evolutionary biology to deduce trees of relationships among species that best explain the available data.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayes-theorem] This approach was made practical by the use of Markov chain Monte Carlo methods.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference derives the posterior probability as a consequence of two antecedents: a prior probability and a "likelihood function" derived from a statistical model for the observed data.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] If that term is approximately 1, then the probability of the hypothesis given the evidence, $P(H\mid E)$ , is about ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ , about 50% likely - equally likely or not likely.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] If that term is very small, close to zero, then the probability of the hypothesis, given the evidence, $P(H\mid E)$ is close to 1 or the conditional hypothesis is quite likely.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] If that term is very large, much larger than 1, then the hypothesis, given the evidence, is quite unlikely.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Bayesian updating is widely used and computationally convenient.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] However, it is not the only updating rule that might be considered rational.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Ian Hacking noted that traditional "Dutch book" arguments did not specify Bayesian updating: they left open the possibility that non-Bayesian updating rules could avoid Dutch books.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Hacking wrote: "And neither the Dutch book argument nor any other in the personalist arsenal of proofs of the probability axioms entails the dynamic assumption.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] So the personalist requires the dynamic assumption to be Bayesian.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] It is true that in consistency a personalist could abandon the Bayesian model of learning from experience.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Indeed, there are non-Bayesian updating rules that also avoid Dutch books (as discussed in the literature on "probability kinematics") following the publication of Richard C.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Jeffrey's rule, which applies Bayes' rule to the case where the evidence itself is assigned a probability.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The additional hypotheses needed to uniquely require Bayesian updating have been deemed to be substantial, complicated, and unsatisfactory.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] If evidence is simultaneously used to update belief over a set of exclusive and exhaustive propositions, Bayesian inference may be thought of as acting on this belief distribution as a whole.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Suppose a process is generating independent and identically distributed events $E_{n},\ n=1,2,3,\ldots$ , but the probability distribution is unknown.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Let the event space $\Omega$ represent the current state of belief for this process.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Each model is represented by event $M_{m}$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The conditional probabilities $P(E_{n}\mid M_{m})$ are specified to define the models. $P(M_{m})$ is the degree of belief in $M_{m}$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Before the first inference step, $\{P(M_{m})\}$ is a set of *initial prior probabilities*.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] These must sum to 1, but are otherwise arbitrary.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Suppose that the process is observed to generate $E\in \{E_{n}\}$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] For each $M\in \{M_{m}\}$ , the prior $P(M)$ is updated to the posterior $P(M\mid E)$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Upon observation of further evidence, this procedure may be repeated.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] By parameterizing the space of models, the belief in all models may be updated in a single step.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The distribution of belief over the model space may then be thought of as a distribution of belief over the parameter space.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The distributions in this section are expressed as continuous, represented by probability densities, as this is the usual situation.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The technique is, however, equally applicable to discrete distributions.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Let the vector ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ span the parameter space.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Let the initial prior distribution over ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ be $p({\boldsymbol {\theta }}\mid {\boldsymbol {\alpha }})$ , where ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}$ is a set of parameters to the prior itself, or *hyperparameters*.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Let $\mathbf {E} =(e_{1},\dots ,e_{n})$ be a sequence of independent and identically distributed event observations, where all $e_{i}$ are distributed as $p(e\mid {\boldsymbol {\theta }})$ for some ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] This is expressed in words as "posterior is proportional to likelihood times prior", or sometimes as "posterior = likelihood times prior, over evidence".
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] $P_{X}^{y}(A)=E(1_{A}(X)|Y=y)$ Existence and uniqueness of the needed conditional expectation is a consequence of the Radon–Nikodym theorem.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] This was formulated by Kolmogorov in his famous book from 1933.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Kolmogorov underlines the importance of conditional probability by writing "I wish to call attention to ... and especially the theory of conditional probabilities and conditional expectations ..." in the Preface.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The Bayes theorem determines the posterior distribution from the prior distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Modern Markov chain Monte Carlo methods have boosted the importance of Bayes' theorem including cases with improper priors.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Bayesian theory calls for the use of the posterior predictive distribution to do predictive inference, i.e., to predict the distribution of a new, unobserved data point.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] That is, instead of a fixed point as a prediction, a distribution over possible points is returned.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Only this way is the entire posterior distribution of the parameter(s) used.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] By comparison, prediction in frequentist statistics often involves finding an optimum point estimate of the parameter(s)—e.g., by maximum likelihood or maximum a posteriori estimation (MAP)—and then plugging this estimate into the formula for the distribution of a data point.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] This has the disadvantage that it does not account for any uncertainty in the value of the parameter, and hence will underestimate the variance of the predictive distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] In some instances, frequentist statistics can work around this problem.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] For example, confidence intervals and prediction intervals in frequentist statistics when constructed from a normal distribution with unknown mean and variance are constructed using a Student's t-distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] In Bayesian statistics, however, the posterior predictive distribution can always be determined exactly—or at least to an arbitrary level of precision when numerical methods are used.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Both types of predictive distributions have the form of a compound probability distribution (as does the marginal likelihood).
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] In fact, if the prior distribution is a conjugate prior, such that the prior and posterior distributions come from the same family, it can be seen that both prior and posterior predictive distributions also come from the same family of compound distributions.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] That is, if the model were true, the evidence would be more likely than is predicted by the current state of belief.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The reverse applies for a decrease in belief.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] If the belief does not change, ${\textstyle {\frac {P(E\mid M)}{P(E)}}=1\Rightarrow P(E\mid M)=P(E)}$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] That is, the evidence is independent of the model.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] If the model were true, the evidence would be exactly as likely as predicted by the current state of belief.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] This can be interpreted to mean that hard convictions are insensitive to counter-evidence.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The former follows directly from Bayes' theorem.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The latter can be derived by applying the first rule to the event "not M " in place of " M ", yielding "if $1-P(M)=0$ , then $1-P(M\mid E)=0$ ", from which the result immediately follows.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Consider the behaviour of a belief distribution as it is updated a large number of times with independent and identically distributed trials.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] For sufficiently nice prior probabilities, the Bernstein-von Mises theorem gives that in the limit of infinite trials, the posterior converges to a Gaussian distribution independent of the initial prior under some conditions firstly outlined and rigorously proven by Joseph L.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Doob in 1948, namely if the random variable in consideration has a finite probability space.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The more general results were obtained later by the statistician David A.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Freedman who published in two seminal research papers in 1963 and 1965 when and under what circumstances the asymptotic behaviour of posterior is guaranteed.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] His 1963 paper treats, like Doob (1949), the finite case and comes to a satisfactory conclusion.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] However, if the random variable has an infinite but countable probability space (i.e., corresponding to a die with infinite many faces) the 1965 paper demonstrates that for a dense subset of priors the Bernstein-von Mises theorem is not applicable.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] In this case there is almost surely no asymptotic convergence.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Later in the 1980s and 1990s Freedman and Persi Diaconis continued to work on the case of infinite countable probability spaces.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] To summarise, there may be insufficient trials to suppress the effects of the initial choice, and especially for large (but finite) systems the convergence might be very slow.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] In parameterized form, the prior distribution is often assumed to come from a family of distributions called conjugate priors.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The usefulness of a conjugate prior is that the corresponding posterior distribution will be in the same family, and the calculation may be expressed in closed form.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] It is often desired to use a posterior distribution to estimate a parameter or variable.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Several methods of Bayesian estimation select measurements of central tendency from the posterior distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] For one-dimensional problems, a unique median exists for practical continuous problems.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The posterior median is attractive as a robust estimator.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] There are examples where no maximum is attained, in which case the set of MAP estimates is empty.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] There are other methods of estimation that minimize the posterior risk (expected-posterior loss) with respect to a loss function, and these are of interest to statistical decision theory using the sampling distribution (frequentist statistics).
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Suppose there are two full bowls of cookies.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Bowl #1 has 10 chocolate chip and 30 plain cookies, while bowl #2 has 20 of each.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Fred picks a bowl at random and then picks a cookie at random, which means that there is no reason to believe Fred treats one bowl differently from another, likewise for the cookies.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] As to how probable it is that Fred picked it out of bowl #1, that is an example of a Bayesian inference-approachable problem.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Intuitively, it seems clear that the answer should be more than a half, since there are more plain cookies in bowl #1.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The precise answer is given by Bayes' theorem.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] It is given that the bowls are identical from Fred's point of view, thus $P(H_{1})=P(H_{2})$ , and the two must add up to 1, so both are equal to 0.5.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The event E is the observation of a plain cookie.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] An archaeologist is working at a site thought to be from the medieval period, between the 11th century to the 16th century.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] However, it is uncertain exactly when in this period the site was inhabited.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Fragments of pottery are found, some of which are glazed and some of which are decorated.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] It is expected that if the site were inhabited during the early medieval period, then 1% of the pottery would be glazed and 50% of its area decorated, whereas if it had been inhabited in the late medieval period then 81% would be glazed and 5% of its area decorated.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] How confident can the archaeologist be in the date of inhabitation as fragments are unearthed?
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The degree of belief in the continuous variable C (century) is to be calculated, with the discrete set of events $\{GD,G{\bar {D}},{\bar {G}}D,{\bar {G}}{\bar {D}}\}$ as evidence.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] When a new fragment of type e is discovered, that means *more information* for the investigation and, through Bayes' theorem, an *updated* Bayesian inference towards an improved degree of belief (or confidence) in the archeologists' estimation.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] A computer simulation of the changing belief as 50 fragments are unearthed is shown on the graph.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] In the simulation, the site was inhabited around 1420, or $c=15.2$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The Bernstein-von Mises theorem asserts here the asymptotic convergence to the "true" distribution because the probability space corresponding to the discrete set of events $\{GD,G{\bar {D}},{\bar {G}}D,{\bar {G}}{\bar {D}}\}$ is finite (see above section on asymptotic behaviour of the posterior).
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] A decision-theoretic justification of the use of Bayesian inference was given by Abraham Wald, who proved that every unique Bayesian procedure is admissible.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Conversely, every admissible statistical procedure is either a Bayesian procedure or a limit of Bayesian procedures.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Wald characterized admissible procedures as Bayesian procedures (and limits of Bayesian procedures), making the Bayesian formalism a central technique in such areas of frequentist inference as parameter estimation, hypothesis testing, and computing confidence intervals.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Bayesian methodology also plays a role in model selection where the aim is to select one model from a set of competing models that represents most closely the underlying process that generated the observed data.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] In Bayesian model comparison, the model with the highest posterior probability given the data is selected.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The posterior probability of a model depends on the evidence, or marginal likelihood, which reflects the probability that the data is generated by the model, and on the prior belief of the model.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] When two competing models are a priori considered to be equiprobable, the ratio of their posterior probabilities corresponds to the Bayes factor.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Since Bayesian model comparison is aimed on selecting the model with the highest posterior probability, this methodology is also referred to as the maximum a posteriori (MAP) selection rule or the MAP probability rule.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] While conceptually simple, Bayesian methods can be mathematically and numerically challenging.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Probabilistic programming languages (PPLs) implement functions to easily build Bayesian models together with efficient automatic inference methods.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] This helps separate the model building from the inference, allowing practitioners to focus on their specific problems and leaving PPLs to handle the computational details for them.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] See the separate Wikipedia entry on Bayesian statistics, specifically the statistical modeling section in that page.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference has applications in artificial intelligence and expert systems.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference techniques have been a fundamental part of computerized pattern recognition techniques since the late 1950s.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Recently Bayesian inference has gained popularity among the phylogenetics community for these reasons; a number of applications allow many demographic and evolutionary parameters to be estimated simultaneously.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] As applied to statistical classification, Bayesian inference has been used to develop algorithms for identifying e-mail spam.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Applications which make use of Bayesian inference for spam filtering include CRM114, DSPAM, Bogofilter, SpamAssassin, SpamBayes, Mozilla, XEAMS, and others.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Spam classification is treated in more detail in the article on the naïve Bayes classifier.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Solomonoff's Inductive inference is the theory of prediction based on observations; for example, predicting the next symbol based upon a given series of symbols.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The only assumption is that the environment follows some unknown but computable probability distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] It is a formal inductive framework that combines two well-studied principles of inductive inference: Bayesian statistics and Occam's Razor.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Solomonoff's universal prior probability of any prefix *p* of a computable sequence *x* is the sum of the probabilities of all programs (for a universal computer) that compute something starting with *p*.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Given some *p* and any computable but unknown probability distribution from which *x* is sampled, the universal prior and Bayes' theorem can be used to predict the yet unseen parts of *x* in optimal fashion.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference has been applied in different bioinformatics applications, including differential gene expression analysis.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference is also used in a general cancer risk model, called CIRI (Continuous Individualized Risk Index), where serial measurements are incorporated to update a Bayesian model which is primarily built from prior knowledge.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] In cosmology, it is often employed with computational techniques such as Markov chain Monte Carlo(MCMC) and Nested sampling algorithm to analyse complex datasets and navigate high-dimensional parameter space.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] A notable application is to the Planck 2018 CMB data for parameter inference.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The six base cosmological parameters in Lambda-CDM model are not predicted by a theory, but rather fitted from Cosmic microwave background (CMB) data to a chosen model of cosmology (the Lambda-CDM model).
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The bayesian code for cosmology `cobaya` sets up cosmological runs and interfaces cosmological likelihoods, Boltzmann code, which computes the predicted CMB anisotropies for any given set of cosmological parameters, with MCMC or nested sampler.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] This computational framework is not limited to the standard model, it is also essential for testing alternative or extended theories of cosmology, such as theories with early dark energy, or modified gravity theories introducing additional parameters beyond Lambda-CDM.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Bayesian model comparison can then be employed to calculate the evidence for competing models, providing a statistical basis to assess whether the data support them over the standard Lambda-CDM.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference can be used by jurors to coherently accumulate the evidence for and against a defendant, and to see whether, in totality, it meets their personal threshold for "beyond a reasonable doubt".
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Bayes' theorem is applied successively to all evidence presented, with the posterior from one stage becoming the prior for the next.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The benefit of a Bayesian approach is that it gives the juror an unbiased, rational mechanism for combining evidence.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] It may be appropriate to explain Bayes' theorem to jurors in odds form, as betting odds are more widely understood than probabilities.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Alternatively, a logarithmic approach, replacing multiplication with addition, might be easier for a jury to handle.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] If the existence of the crime is not in doubt, only the identity of the culprit, it has been suggested that the prior should be uniform over the qualifying population.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] For example, if 1,000 people could have committed the crime, the prior probability of guilt would be 1/1000.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The use of Bayes' theorem by jurors is controversial.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] In the United Kingdom, a defence expert witness explained Bayes' theorem to the jury in *R v Adams*.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The jury convicted, but the case went to appeal on the basis that no means of accumulating evidence had been provided for jurors who did not wish to use Bayes' theorem.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Gardner-Medwin argues that the criterion on which a verdict in a criminal trial should be based is *not* the probability of guilt, but rather the *probability of the evidence, given that the defendant is innocent* (akin to a frequentist p-value).
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] He argues that if the posterior probability of guilt is to be computed by Bayes' theorem, the prior probability of guilt must be known.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] This will depend on the incidence of the crime, which is an unusual piece of evidence to consider in a criminal trial.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] – the known facts and testimony could have arisen if the defendant is guilty.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] – the known facts and testimony could have arisen if the defendant is innocent.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Gardner-Medwin argues that the jury should believe both *A* and not-*B* in order to convict.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] *A* and not-*B* implies the truth of *C*, but the reverse is not true.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] It is possible that *B* and *C* are both true, but in this case he argues that a jury should acquit, even though they know that they will be letting some guilty people go free.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Bayesian epistemology is a movement that advocates for Bayesian inference as a means of justifying the rules of inductive logic.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Karl Popper and David Miller have rejected the idea of Bayesian rationalism, i.e. using Bayes rule to make epistemological inferences: It is prone to the same vicious circle as any other justificationist epistemology, because it presupposes what it attempts to justify.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The problem considered by Bayes in Proposition 9 of his essay, "An Essay Towards Solving a Problem in the Doctrine of Chances", is the posterior distribution for the parameter *a* (the success rate) of the binomial distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] The term 'Bayesian' refers to Thomas Bayes (1701–1761), who proved that probabilistic limits could be placed on an unknown event.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] However, it was Pierre-Simon Laplace (1749–1827) who introduced (as Principle VI) what is now called Bayes' theorem and used it to address problems in celestial mechanics, medical statistics, reliability, and jurisprudence.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Early Bayesian inference, which used uniform priors following Laplace's principle of insufficient reason, was called inverse probability (because it infers backwards from observations to parameters, or from effects to causes).
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] After the 1920s, inverse probability was largely supplanted by a collection of methods that came to be called frequentist statistics.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] In the 20th century, the ideas of Laplace were further developed in two different directions, giving rise to *objective* and *subjective* currents in Bayesian practice.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] In the objective (or "non-informative") current, the statistical analysis depends only on the model assumed, the data analyzed, and the method assigning the prior, which differs from one objective Bayesian practitioner to another.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] In the subjective (or "informative") current, the specification of the prior depends on the belief—the propositions on which the analysis is prepared to act—which can summarize information from experts, previous studies, etc.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] In the 1980s, there was a dramatic growth in research and applications of Bayesian methods, mostly attributed to the discovery of Markov chain Monte Carlo methods, which removed many of the computational problems, and an increasing interest in nonstandard, complex applications.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Despite growth of Bayesian research, most undergraduate teaching is still based on frequentist statistics.
[src:bayesian-inference/bayesian-inference] Nonetheless, Bayesian methods are widely accepted and used, such as for example in the field of machine learning.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In statistics, **Markov chain Monte Carlo** (**MCMC**) is a class of algorithms used to draw samples from a probability distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Given a probability distribution, one can construct a Markov chain whose elements' distribution approximates it, i.e. the Markov chain's equilibrium distribution matches the target distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The more steps that are included, the more closely the distribution of the sample matches the actual desired distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain Monte Carlo methods are used to study probability distributions that are too complex or too high dimensional to study with analytic techniques alone.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Various algorithms exist for constructing such Markov chains, including the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain Monte Carlo methods create samples from a continuous random variable, with probability density proportional to a known function.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These samples can be used to evaluate an integral over that variable, as its expected value or variance.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Practically, an ensemble of chains is generally developed, starting from a set of points arbitrarily chosen and sufficiently distant from each other.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These chains are stochastic processes of "walkers" which move around randomly according to an algorithm that looks for places with a reasonably high contribution to the integral to move into next, assigning them higher probabilities.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Random walk Monte Carlo methods are a kind of random simulation or Monte Carlo method.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, whereas the random samples of the integrand used in a conventional Monte Carlo integration are statistically independent, those used in MCMC are autocorrelated.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Correlations of samples introduces the need to use the Markov chain central limit theorem when estimating the error of mean values.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These algorithms create Markov chains such that they have an equilibrium distribution which is proportional to the function given.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The development of MCMC methods is deeply rooted in the early exploration of Monte Carlo (MC) techniques in the mid-20th century, particularly in physics.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These developments were marked by the Metropolis algorithm proposed by Nicholas Metropolis, Arianna W.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Rosenbluth, Marshall Rosenbluth, Augusta H.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Teller, and Edward Teller in 1953, which was designed to tackle high-dimensional integration problems using early computers.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Hastings generalized this algorithm and inadvertently introduced the component-wise updating idea, later known as Gibbs sampling.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Simultaneously, the theoretical foundations for Gibbs sampling were being developed, such as the Hammersley–Clifford theorem from Julian Besag's 1974 paper.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Although the seeds of MCMC were sown earlier, including the formal naming of Gibbs sampling in image processing by Stuart Geman and Donald Geman (1984) and the data augmentation method by Martin A.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This transformation was accompanied by significant theoretical advancements, such as Luke Tierney's (1994) rigorous treatment of MCMC convergence, and Jun S.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Liu, Wong, and Augustine Kong's (1994, 1995) analysis of Gibbs sampler structure.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Subsequent developments further expanded the MCMC toolkit, including particle filters (Sequential Monte Carlo) for sequential problems, Perfect sampling aiming for exact simulation (Jim Propp and David B.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Green, 1995) for handling variable-dimension models, and deeper investigations into convergence diagnostics and the central limit theorem.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overall, the evolution of MCMC represents a paradigm shift in statistical computation, enabling the analysis of numerous previously intractable complex models and continually expanding the scope and impact of statistics.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Suppose *(Xn)* is a Markov Chain in the general state space ${\mathcal {X}}$ with specific properties.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Particularly, we hope to establish the Law of Large Numbers and the Central Limit Theorem for MCMC.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the following, we state some definitions and theorems necessary for the important convergence results.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In short, we need the existence of invariant measure and Harris recurrent to establish the Law of Large Numbers of MCMC (Ergodic Theorem).
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] And we need aperiodicity, irreducibility and extra conditions such as reversibility to ensure the Central Limit Theorem holds in MCMC.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Recall that in the discrete setting, a Markov chain is said to be *irreducible* if it is possible to reach any state from any other state in a finite number of steps with positive probability.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, in the continuous setting, point-to-point transitions have zero probability.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In this case, **φ-irreducibility** generalizes irreducibility by using a reference measure φ on the measurable space $({\mathcal {X}},{\mathcal {B}}({\mathcal {X}}))$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This is a more general definition for irreducibility of a Markov chain in non-discrete state space.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the discrete case, an irreducible Markov chain is said to be *aperiodic* if it has period 1.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The chain $(X_{n})$ is said to be **Harris recurrent** if there exists a measure $\psi$ such that the chain is $\psi$ -irreducible and every measurable set A with $\psi (A)>0$ is Harris recurrent.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This definition is only needed when the state space ${\mathcal {X}}$ is uncountable.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the countable case, recurrence corresponds to $\mathbb {E} _{x}[\eta _{x}]=\infty$ , which is equivalent to $P_{x}(\tau _{x}<\infty )=1$ for all $x\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When there exists an *invariant probability measure* for a **ψ-irreducible** (hence recurrent) chain, the chain is said to be **positive recurrent**.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Recurrent chains that do not allow for a finite invariant measure are called **null recurrent**.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In applications of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC), a very useful criterion for Harris recurrence involves the use of bounded harmonic functions.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These functions are *invariant* under the transition kernel in the functional sense, and they help characterize Harris recurrence.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This theorem provides a fundamental justification for the use of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods, and it serves as the counterpart of the Law of Large Numbers (LLN) in classical Monte Carlo.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] An important aspect of this result is that $\pi$ does not need to be a probability measure.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Therefore, there can be some type of strong stability even if the chain is null recurrent.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Moreover, the Markov chain can be started from arbitrary state.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This is the Ergodic Theorem that we are more familiar with.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] There are several conditions under which the Central Limit Theorem (CLT) holds for Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One of the most commonly used is the condition of **reversibility**.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] A stationary Markov chain $(X_{n})$ is said to be **reversible** if the distribution of $X_{n+1}$ given $X_{n+2}=x$ is the same as the distribution of $X_{n+1}$ given $X_{n}=x$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] for every pair $(x,y)$ in the state space.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Even though reversibility is a restrictive assumption in theory, it is often easily satisfied in practical MCMC algorithms by introducing auxiliary variables or using symmetric proposal mechanisms.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] There are many other conditions that can be used to establish CLT for MCMC such as geometric ergodicity and the discrete state space.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] MCMC methods produce autocorrelated samples, in contrast to standard Monte Carlo techniques that draw independent samples.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Autocorrelation means successive draws from the Markov chain are statistically dependent, so each new sample adds less fresh information than an independent draw would.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] As a result, one must account for this correlation when assessing the accuracy of estimates from the chain.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In particular, positive autocorrelation in the chain increases the variance of estimators and slows the convergence of sample averages toward the true expectation.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The effect of correlation on estimation can be quantified through the Markov chain central limit theorem.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For a chain targeting a distribution with variance $\sigma ^{2}$ , the variance of the sample mean after N steps is approximately ${\sigma ^{2}}{\big /}N_{\text{eff}}$ , where $N_{\text{eff}}$ is an effective sample size smaller than N .
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The term in parentheses, $1+2\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\rho _{k}$ , is often called the integrated autocorrelation.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When the chain has no autocorrelation ( $\rho _{k}=0$ for all $k\geq 1$ ), this factor equals 1, and one recovers the usual $\sigma ^{2}/N$ variance for independent samples.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the chain's samples are highly correlated, the sum of autocorrelations is large, leading to a much bigger variance for ${\bar {X}}_{N}$ than in the independent case.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The effective sample size $N_{\text{eff}}$ is a useful diagnostic that translates the autocorrelation in a chain into an equivalent number of independent samples.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] so that $N_{\text{eff}}$ is the number of independent draws that would yield the same estimation precision as the N dependent draws from the Markov chain.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For example, if $1+2\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\rho _{k}=5$ , then $N_{\text{eff}}=N/5$ , meaning the chain of length N carries information equivalent to $N/5$ independent samples.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In an ideal scenario with no correlation, $\rho _{k}=0$ and thus $N_{\text{eff}}\approx N$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] But in a poorly mixing chain with strong autocorrelation, $N_{\text{eff}}$ can be much smaller than N .
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, monitoring the ESS for each parameter is a way to gauge how much correlation is present: a low ESS indicates that many more iterations may be needed to achieve a desired effective sample of independent draws.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One way to address this problem could be shortening the steps of the walker, so that it does not continuously try to exit the highest probability region, though this way the process would be highly autocorrelated and expensive (i.e. many steps would be required for an accurate result).
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] More sophisticated methods such as Hamiltonian Monte Carlo and the Wang and Landau algorithm use various ways of reducing this autocorrelation, while managing to keep the process in the regions that give a higher contribution to the integral.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These algorithms usually rely on a more complicated theory and are harder to implement, but they usually converge faster.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] We outline several general strategies such as reparameterization, adaptive proposal tuning, parameter blocking, and overrelaxation that help reduce correlation and improve sampling efficiency within the standard MCMC framework.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One way to reduce autocorrelation is to reformulate or reparameterize the statistical model so that the posterior geometry leads to more efficient sampling.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] By changing the coordinate system or using alternative variable definitions, one can often lessen correlations.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For example, in Bayesian hierarchical modeling, a non-centered parameterization can be used in place of the standard (centered) formulation to avoid extreme posterior correlations between latent and higher-level parameters.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This involves expressing latent variables in terms of independent auxiliary variables, dramatically improving mixing.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Such reparameterization strategies are commonly employed in both Gibbs sampling and Metropolis–Hastings algorithm to enhance convergence and reduce autocorrelation.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Another approach to reducing correlation is to improve the MCMC proposal mechanism.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, step size tuning is critical: if the proposed steps are too small, the sampler moves slowly and produces highly correlated samples; if the steps are too large, many proposals are rejected, resulting in repeated values.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Adjusting the proposal step size during an initial testing phase helps find a balance where the sampler explores the space efficiently without too many rejections.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Adaptive MCMC methods modify proposal distributions based on the chain's past samples.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For instance, the adaptive Metropolis algorithm updates the Gaussian proposal distribution using the full information accumulated from the chain so far, allowing the proposal to adapt over time.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Parameter blocking is a technique that reduces autocorrelation in MCMC by updating parameters jointly rather than one at a time.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When parameters exhibit strong posterior correlations, one-by-one updates can lead to poor mixing and slow exploration of the target distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] By identifying and sampling blocks of correlated parameters together, the sampler can more effectively traverse high-density regions of the posterior.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Parameter blocking is commonly used in both Gibbs sampling and Metropolis–Hastings algorithms.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In blocked Gibbs sampling, entire groups of variables are updated conditionally at each step.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Metropolis–Hastings, multivariate proposals enable joint updates (i.e., updates of multiple parameters at once using a vector-valued proposal distribution, typically a multivariate Gaussian), though they often require careful tuning of the proposal covariance matrix.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overrelaxation is a technique to reduce autocorrelation between successive samples by proposing new samples that are negatively correlated with the current state.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This helps the chain explore the posterior more efficiently, especially in high-dimensional Gaussian models or when using Gibbs sampling.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The basic idea is to reflect the current sample across the conditional mean, producing proposals that retain the correct stationary distribution but with reduced serial dependence.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overrelaxation is particularly effective when combined with Gaussian conditional distributions, where exact reflection or partial overrelaxation can be analytically implemented.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Interacting MCMC methodologies are a class of mean-field particle methods for obtaining random samples from a sequence of probability distributions with an increasing level of sampling complexity.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In principle, any Markov chain Monte Carlo sampler can be turned into an interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo sampler.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers can be interpreted as a way to run in parallel a sequence of Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For instance, interacting simulated annealing algorithms are based on independent Metropolis–Hastings moves interacting sequentially with a selection-resampling type mechanism.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In contrast to traditional Markov chain Monte Carlo methods, the precision parameter of this class of interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers is *only* related to the number of interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These advanced particle methodologies belong to the class of Feynman–Kac particle models, also called Sequential Monte Carlo or particle filter methods in Bayesian inference and signal processing communities.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo methods can also be interpreted as a mutation-selection genetic particle algorithm with Markov chain Monte Carlo mutations.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The quasi-Monte Carlo method is an analog to the normal Monte Carlo method that uses low-discrepancy sequences instead of random numbers.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] It yields an integration error that decays faster than that of true random sampling, as quantified by the Koksma–Hlawka inequality.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Empirically it allows the reduction of both estimation error and convergence time by an order of magnitude.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain quasi-Monte Carlo methods such as the Array–RQMC method combine randomized quasi–Monte Carlo and Markov chain simulation by simulating n chains simultaneously in a way that better approximates the true distribution of the chain than with ordinary MCMC.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In empirical experiments, the variance of the average of a function of the state sometimes converges at rate $O(n^{-2})$ or even faster, instead of the $O(n^{-1})$ Monte Carlo rate.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] MCMC methods are primarily used for calculating numerical approximations of multi-dimensional integrals, for example in Bayesian statistics, computational physics, computational biology and computational linguistics.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Bayesian statistics, Markov chain Monte Carlo methods are typically used to calculate moments and credible intervals of posterior probability distributions.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The use of MCMC methods makes it possible to compute large hierarchical models that require integrations over hundreds to thousands of unknown parameters.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Many contemporary research problems in statistical physics can be addressed by approximate solutions using Monte Carlo simulation, which provides valuable insights into the properties of complex systems.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Monte Carlo methods are fundamental in computational physics, astrophysics, physical chemistry, and related disciplines, with broad applications including medical physics, where they are employed to model radiation transport for radiation dosimetry calculations.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Instead of exhaustively analyzing all possible system states, the Monte Carlo method randomly examines a subset of them to form a representative sample, and yields accurate approximations of the system's characteristic properties.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] As the number of sampled states increases, the error can be further reduced to a lower level.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Langevin Dynamics are typically used in complex distribution sampling and generative modeling, via an MCMC procedure.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Specifically, given the probability density function $p(x)$ , we use its log gradient $\nabla _{x}\log p(x)$ as the score function and start from a prior distribution $x_{0}\sim p_{0}$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When $\epsilon \rightarrow 0$ and $K\rightarrow \infty$ , $x_{K}$ converges to a sample from the target distribution $p(x)$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For some complex distribution, if we know its probability density function but find it difficult to directly sample from it, we can apply Langevin Dynamics as an alternate.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, in most cases, especially generative modeling, usually we do not know the exact probability density function of the target distribution we wish to sample from, neither the score function $\nabla _{x}\log p(x)$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In this case, score matching methods provide feasible solutions, minimizing the Fisher information metric between a parameterized score-based model $s_{\theta }(x)$ and the score function without knowing the ground-truth data score.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The score function can be estimated on a training dataset by stochastic gradient descent.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In real cases, however, the training data only takes a small region of the target distribution, and the estimated score functions are inaccurate in other low density regions with fewer available data examples.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] To overcome this challenge, denoising score matching methods perturb the available data examples with noise of different scales, which can improve the coverage of low density regions, and use them as the training dataset for the score-base model.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Note that the choice of noise scales is tricky, as too large noise will corrupt the original data, while too small noise will not populate the original data to those low density regions.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Thus, carefully crafted noise schedules are applied for higher quality generation.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Usually it is not hard to construct a Markov chain with the desired properties.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The more difficult problem is to determine (1) when to start collecting statistics and (2) how many steps are needed to converge to the stationary distribution within an acceptable error.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Fortunately, there are a variety of practical diagnostics to empirically assess convergence.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Formally, let $\pi$ denote the stationary distribution and $P^{t}(x,\cdot )$ the distribution of the Markov chain after t steps starting from state x .
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] A chain is said to mix rapidly if $d_{\text{TV}}(P^{t}(x,\cdot ),\pi )\leq \epsilon$ for all $x\in {\mathcal {X}}$ within a small number of steps t under a pre-defined tolerance $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In other words, the stationary distribution is reached quickly starting from an arbitrary position, and the minimum such t is known as the mixing time.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, however, the total variation distance is generally intractable to compute, especially in high-dimensional problems or when the stationary distribution is only known up to a normalizing constant (as in most Bayesian applications).
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Gelman-Rubin statistic, also known as the **potential scale reduction factor (PSRF)**, evaluates MCMC convergence by sampling multiple independent Markov chains and comparing within-chain and between-chain variances.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If all chains have converged to the same stationary distribution, the between-chain and within-chain variances should be similar, and thus the PSRF must approach 1.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, a value of $<1.1$ is often taken as evidence of convergence.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Higher values suggest that the chains are still exploring different parts of the target distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Geweke diagnostic examines whether the distribution of samples in the early part of the Markov chain is statistically indistinguishable from the distribution in a later part.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Since MCMC samples are autocorrelated, a simple comparison of sample means is insufficient.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Instead, the difference in means is standardized using an estimator of the spectral density at zero frequency, which accounts for the long-range dependencies in the chain.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\hat {S}}(0)$ is an estimate of the long-run variance (i.e., the spectral density at frequency zero), commonly estimated using Newey-West estimators or batch means.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Under the null hypothesis of convergence, the statistic Z follows an approximately standard normal distribution $Z\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If $|Z|>1.96$ , the null hypothesis is rejected at the 5% significance level, suggesting that the chain has not yet reached stationarity.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Heidelberger-Welch diagnostic is grounded in spectral analysis and Brownian motion theory, and is particularly useful in the early stages of simulation to determine appropriate burn-in and stopping time.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The diagnostic consists of two components, a **stationarity test** that assesses whether the Markov chain has reached a steady-state, and a **half-width test** that determines whether the estimated expectation is within a user-specified precision.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Let $\{X_{t}\}_{t=1}^{n}$ be the output of an MCMC simulation for a scalar function $g(X_{t})$ , and $g_{1},g_{2},\dots ,g_{n}$ the evaluations of the function g over the chain.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\bar {g}}_{n}={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}g_{i}$ is the sample mean and ${\hat {S}}(0)$ is an estimate of the spectral density at frequency zero.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Under the null hypothesis of convergence, the process $B_{n}(t)$ converges in distribution to a Brownian bridge.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This statistic is compared against known critical values from the Brownian bridge distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the null hypothesis is rejected, the first 10% of the samples are discarded and the test can be repeated on the remaining chain until either stationarity is accepted or 50% of the chain is discarded.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Once stationarity is accepted, the second part of the diagnostic checks whether the Monte Carlo estimator is accurate enough for practical use.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ is an estimate of the variance of $g(X)$ , $t_{\alpha /2,\nu }$ is the Student's t critical value at confidence level $1-\alpha$ and degrees of freedom $\nu$ , n is the number of samples used.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the half-width is smaller than a user-defined tolerance (e.g., 0.05), the chain is considered long enough to estimate the expectation reliably.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Otherwise, the simulation should be extended.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Raftery-Lewis diagnostic is specifically designed to assess how many iterations are needed to estimate quantiles or tail probabilities of the target distribution with a desired accuracy and confidence.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Unlike Gelman-Rubin or Geweke diagnostics, which are based on assessing convergence to the entire distribution, the Raftery-Lewis diagnostic is goal-oriented as it provides estimates for the number of samples required to estimate a specific quantile of interest within a desired margin of error.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Let q denote the desired quantile (e.g., 0.025) of a real-valued function $g(X)$ : in other words, the goal is to find u such that $P(g(X)\leq u)=q$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Suppose we wish to estimate this quantile such that the estimate falls within margin $\varepsilon$ of the true value with probability $1-\alpha$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where $I(\cdot )$ is the indicator function.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The sequence $\{W_{n}\}$ is treated as a realization from a two-state Markov chain.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] While this may not be strictly true, it is often a good approximation in practice.
[src:bayesian-inference/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where $\Phi ^{-1}(\cdot )$ is the standard normal quantile function.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] The **posterior probability** is a type of conditional probability that results from updating the prior probability with information summarized by the likelihood via an application of Bayes' rule.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] From an epistemological perspective, the posterior probability contains everything there is to know about an uncertain proposition (such as a scientific hypothesis, or parameter values), given prior knowledge and a mathematical model describing the observations available at a particular time.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] After the arrival of new information, the current posterior probability may serve as the prior in another round of Bayesian updating.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] In the context of Bayesian statistics, the **posterior probability distribution** usually describes the epistemic uncertainty about statistical parameters conditional on a collection of observed data.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] From a given posterior distribution, various point and interval estimates can be derived, such as the maximum a posteriori (MAP) or the highest posterior density interval (HPDI).
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] But while conceptually simple, the posterior distribution is generally not tractable and therefore needs to be either analytically or numerically approximated.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] In Bayesian statistics, the posterior probability is the probability distribution of the parameters $\theta$ given the evidence X , and is denoted $p(\theta |X)$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] It contrasts with the likelihood function, which is the probability of the evidence given the parameters: $p(X|\theta )$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] for continuous $\theta$ , or by summing $p(x|\theta )p(\theta )$ over all possible values of $\theta$ for discrete $\theta$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] The posterior probability is therefore proportional to the product *Likelihood · Prior probability*.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] Suppose there is a school with 60% boys and 40% girls as students.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] The girls wear trousers or skirts in equal numbers; all boys wear trousers.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] An observer sees a (random) student from a distance; all the observer can see is that this student is wearing trousers.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] What is the probability this student is a girl?
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] The correct answer can be computed using Bayes' theorem.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] The event G is that the student observed is a girl, and the event T is that the student observed is wearing trousers.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] An intuitive way to solve this is to assume the school has *N* students.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] Number of boys = 0.6*N* and number of girls = 0.4*N*.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] If *N* is large enough that rounding errors can be ignored, total number of trouser wearers = 0.6*N* + 50% of 0.4*N*.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] And number of girl trouser wearers = 50% of 0.4*N*.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] In other words, if you separated out the group of trouser wearers, a quarter of that group will be girls.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] Therefore, if you see trousers, the most you can deduce is that you are looking at a single sample from a subset of students where 25% are girls.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] And by definition, chance of this random student being a girl is 25%.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] Every Bayes-theorem problem can be solved in this way.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] Posterior probability is a conditional probability conditioned on randomly observed data.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] For a random variable, it is important to summarize its amount of uncertainty.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] One way to achieve this goal is to provide a credible interval of the posterior probability.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] In classification, posterior probabilities reflect the uncertainty of assessing an observation to particular class, see also class-membership probabilities.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] While statistical classification methods by definition generate posterior probabilities, Machine Learners usually supply membership values which do not induce any probabilistic confidence.
[src:bayesian-inference/posterior-probability] It is desirable to transform or rescale membership values to class-membership probabilities, since they are comparable and additionally more easily applicable for post-processing.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] A **prior probability distribution** (often simply called the **prior probability**, **prior distribution**, or **prior**) of an uncertain quantity is its assumed probability distribution before evidence is taken into account.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] For example, the prior could be the probability distribution representing the relative proportions of voters who will vote for a particular politician in a future election.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The unknown quantity may be a parameter of the model or a latent variable rather than an observable variable.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In Bayesian statistics, Bayes' rule prescribes how to update the prior with new information to obtain the posterior probability distribution, which is the conditional distribution of the uncertain quantity given new data.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Historically, the choice of priors was often constrained to a conjugate family of a given likelihood function, so that it would result in a tractable posterior of the same family.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The widespread availability of Markov chain Monte Carlo methods, however, has made this less of a concern.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] There are many ways to construct a prior distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In some cases, a prior may be determined from past information, such as previous experiments.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] A prior can also be *elicited* from the purely subjective assessment of an experienced expert.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] When no information is available, an **uninformative prior** may be adopted as justified by the principle of indifference.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In modern applications, priors are also often chosen for their mechanical properties, such as regularization and feature selection.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The prior distributions of model parameters will often depend on parameters of their own.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Uncertainty about these hyperparameters can, in turn, be expressed as hyperprior probability distributions.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In principle, priors can be decomposed into many conditional levels of distributions, so-called *hierarchical priors*.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] An *informative prior* expresses specific, definite information about a variable.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] An example is a prior distribution for the temperature at noon tomorrow.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] A reasonable approach is to make the prior a normal distribution with expected value equal to today's noontime temperature, with variance equal to the day-to-day variance of atmospheric temperature, or a distribution of the temperature for that day of the year.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The terms "prior" and "posterior" are generally relative to a specific datum or observation.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] A **strong prior** is a preceding assumption, theory, concept or idea upon which, after taking account of new information, a current assumption, theory, concept or idea is founded.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] A strong prior is a type of informative prior in which the information contained in the prior distribution dominates the information contained in the data being analyzed.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The Bayesian analysis combines the information contained in the prior with that extracted from the data to produce the posterior distribution which, in the case of a "strong prior", would be little changed from the prior distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] A *weakly informative prior* expresses partial information about a variable, steering the analysis toward solutions that align with existing knowledge without overly constraining the results and preventing extreme estimates.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] An example is, when setting the prior distribution for the temperature at noon tomorrow in St.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Louis, to use a normal distribution with mean 50 degrees Fahrenheit and standard deviation 40 degrees, which very loosely constrains the temperature to the range (10 degrees, 90 degrees) with a small chance of being below -30 degrees or above 130 degrees.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The purpose of a weakly informative prior is for regularization, that is, to keep inferences in a reasonable range.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] An *uninformative*, *flat*, or *diffuse prior* expresses vague or general information about a variable.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The term "uninformative prior" is somewhat of a misnomer.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Such a prior might also be called a *not very informative prior*, or an *objective prior*, i.e., one that is not subjectively elicited.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Uninformative priors can express "objective" information such as "the variable is positive" or "the variable is less than some limit".
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The simplest and oldest rule for determining a non-informative prior is the principle of indifference, which assigns equal probabilities to all possibilities.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In parameter estimation problems, the use of an uninformative prior typically yields results which are not too different from conventional statistical analysis, as the likelihood function often yields more information than the uninformative prior.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Perhaps the strongest arguments for objective Bayesianism were given by Edwin T.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Jaynes, based mainly on the consequences of symmetries and on the principle of maximum entropy.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] As an example of an a priori prior, due to Jaynes (2003), consider a situation in which one knows a ball has been hidden under one of three cups, A, B, or C, but no other information is available about its location.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In this case a *uniform prior* of *p*(*A*) = *p*(*B*) = *p*(*C*) = 1/3 seems intuitively like the only reasonable choice.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] More formally, we can see that the problem remains the same if we swap around the labels ("A", "B" and "C") of the cups.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] It would therefore be odd to choose a prior for which a permutation of the labels would cause a change in our predictions about which cup the ball will be found under; the uniform prior is the only one which preserves this invariance.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] If one accepts this invariance principle then one can see that the uniform prior is the logically correct prior to represent this state of knowledge.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] As a more contentious example, Jaynes published an argument based on the invariance of the prior under a change of parameters that suggests that the prior representing complete uncertainty about a probability should be the Haldane prior *p*−1(1 − *p*)−1.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The example Jaynes gives is of finding a chemical in a lab and asking whether it will dissolve in water in repeated experiments.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The Haldane prior gives by far the most weight to $p=0$ and $p=1$ , indicating that the sample will either dissolve every time or never dissolve, with equal probability.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] However, if one has observed samples of the chemical to dissolve in one experiment and not to dissolve in another experiment then this prior is updated to the uniform distribution on the interval [0, 1].
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] This is obtained by applying Bayes' theorem to the data set consisting of one observation of dissolving and one of not dissolving, using the above prior.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The Haldane prior is an improper prior distribution (meaning that it has an infinite mass).
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Harold Jeffreys devised a systematic way for designing uninformative priors as e.g., Jeffreys prior *p*−1/2(1 − *p*)−1/2 for the Bernoulli random variable.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Priors can be constructed which are proportional to the Haar measure if the parameter space *X* carries a natural group structure which leaves invariant our Bayesian state of knowledge.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] This can be seen as a generalisation of the invariance principle used to justify the uniform prior over the three cups in the example above.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] For example, in physics we might expect that an experiment will give the same results regardless of our choice of the origin of a coordinate system.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] This induces the group structure of the translation group on *X*, which determines the prior probability as a constant improper prior.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Similarly, some measurements are naturally invariant to the choice of an arbitrary scale (e.g., whether centimeters or inches are used, the physical results should be equal).
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In such a case, the scale group is the natural group structure, and the corresponding prior on *X* is proportional to 1/*x*.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] It sometimes matters whether we use the left-invariant or right-invariant Haar measure.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] For example, the left and right invariant Haar measures on the affine group are not equal.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] 413) argues that the right-invariant Haar measure is the correct choice.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Jaynes, is to use the principle of maximum entropy (MAXENT).
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The motivation is that the Shannon entropy of a probability distribution measures the amount of information contained in the distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The larger the entropy, the less information is provided by the distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Thus, by maximizing the entropy over a suitable set of probability distributions on *X*, one finds the distribution that is least informative in the sense that it contains the least amount of information consistent with the constraints that define the set.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] For example, the maximum entropy prior on a discrete space, given only that the probability is normalized to 1, is the prior that assigns equal probability to each state.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] And in the continuous case, the maximum entropy prior given that the density is normalized with mean zero and unit variance is the standard normal distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The principle of *minimum cross-entropy* generalizes MAXENT to the case of "updating" an arbitrary prior distribution with suitable constraints in the maximum-entropy sense.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] A related idea, reference priors, was introduced by José-Miguel Bernardo.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Here, the idea is to maximize the expected Kullback–Leibler divergence of the posterior distribution relative to the prior.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] This maximizes the expected posterior information about *X* when the prior density is *p*(*x*); thus, in some sense, *p*(*x*) is the "least informative" prior about X.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The reference prior is defined in the asymptotic limit, i.e., one considers the limit of the priors so obtained as the number of data points goes to infinity.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Here, t is a sufficient statistic for some parameter x .
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The inner integral is the KL divergence between the posterior $p(x\mid t)$ and prior $p(x)$ distributions and the result is the weighted mean over all values of t .
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The inner integral in the second part is the integral over t of the joint density $p(x,t)$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In words, KL is the negative expected value over t of the entropy of x conditional on t plus the marginal (i.e., unconditional) entropy of x .
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In the limiting case where the sample size tends to infinity, the Bernstein-von Mises theorem states that the distribution of x conditional on a given observed value of t is normal with a variance equal to the reciprocal of the Fisher information at the 'true' value of x .
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The entropy of a normal density function is equal to half the logarithm of $2\pi ev$ where v is the variance of the distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In this case therefore $H=\log {\sqrt {\frac {2\pi e}{NI(x^{*})}}}$ where N is the arbitrarily large sample size (to which Fisher information is proportional) and $x*$ is the 'true' value.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Since this does not depend on t it can be taken out of the integral, and as this integral is over a probability space it equals one.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Hence we can write the asymptotic form of KL as $KL=-\log \left(1{\sqrt {kI(x^{*})}}\right)-\,\int p(x)\log[p(x)]\,dx$ where k is proportional to the (asymptotically large) sample size.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Indeed, the very idea goes against the philosophy of Bayesian inference in which 'true' values of parameters are replaced by prior and posterior distributions.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] So we remove $x*$ by replacing it with x and taking the expected value of the normal entropy, which we obtain by multiplying by $p(x)$ and integrating over x .
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] This is a quasi-KL divergence ("quasi" in the sense that the square root of the Fisher information may be the kernel of an improper distribution).
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Due to the minus sign, we need to minimise this in order to maximise the KL divergence with which we started.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The minimum value of the last equation occurs where the two distributions in the logarithm argument, improper or not, do not diverge.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] This in turn occurs when the prior distribution is proportional to the square root of the Fisher information of the likelihood function.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Hence in the single parameter case, reference priors and Jeffreys priors are identical, even though Jeffreys has a very different rationale.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Reference priors are often the objective prior of choice in multivariate problems, since other rules (e.g., Jeffreys' rule) may result in priors with problematic behavior.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Objective prior distributions may also be derived from other principles, such as information or coding theory (see e.g., minimum description length) or frequentist statistics (so-called probability matching priors).
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Such methods are used in Solomonoff's theory of inductive inference.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Constructing objective priors have been recently introduced in bioinformatics, and specially inference in cancer systems biology, where sample size is limited and a vast amount of **prior knowledge** is available.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In these methods, either an information theory based criterion, such as KL divergence or log-likelihood function for binary supervised learning problems and mixture model problems.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Philosophical problems associated with uninformative priors are associated with the choice of an appropriate metric, or measurement scale.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Suppose we want a prior for the running speed of a runner who is unknown to us.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] We could specify, say, a normal distribution as the prior for his speed, but alternatively we could specify a normal prior for the time he takes to complete 100 metres, which is proportional to the reciprocal of the first prior.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] These are very different priors, but it is not clear which is to be preferred.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Jaynes' method of transformation groups can answer this question in some situations.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Similarly, if asked to estimate an unknown proportion between 0 and 1, we might say that all proportions are equally likely, and use a uniform prior.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Alternatively, we might say that all orders of magnitude for the proportion are equally likely, the **logarithmic prior**, which is the uniform prior on the logarithm of proportion.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The Jeffreys prior attempts to solve this problem by computing a prior which expresses the same belief no matter which metric is used.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The Jeffreys prior for an unknown proportion *p* is *p*−1/2(1 − *p*)−1/2, which differs from Jaynes' recommendation.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Priors based on notions of algorithmic probability are used in inductive inference as a basis for induction in very general settings.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Practical problems associated with uninformative priors include the requirement that the posterior distribution be proper.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The usual uninformative priors on continuous, unbounded variables are improper.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] This need not be a problem if the posterior distribution is proper.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Another issue of importance is that if an uninformative prior is to be used *routinely*, i.e., with many different data sets, it should have good frequentist properties.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Normally a Bayesian would not be concerned with such issues, but it can be important in this situation.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] For example, one would want any decision rule based on the posterior distribution to be admissible under the adopted loss function.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Admissibility is often difficult to check, although some results are known (e.g., Berger and Strawderman 1996).
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The issue is particularly acute with hierarchical Bayes models; the usual priors (e.g., Jeffreys' prior) may give badly inadmissible decision rules if employed at the higher levels of the hierarchy.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Let events $A_{1},A_{2},\ldots ,A_{n}$ be mutually exclusive and exhaustive.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] If the summation in the denominator converges, the posterior probabilities will still sum (or integrate) to 1 even if the prior values do not, and so the priors may only need to be specified in the correct proportion.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Taking this idea further, in many cases the sum or integral of the prior values may not even need to be finite to get sensible answers for the posterior probabilities.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] When this is the case, the prior is called an **improper prior**.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] However, the posterior distribution need not be a proper distribution if the prior is improper.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] This is clear from the case where event *B* is independent of all of the *A**j*.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Statisticians sometimes use improper priors as uninformative priors.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Many authors (Lindley, 1973; De Groot, 1937; Kass and Wasserman, 1996) warn against the danger of over-interpreting those priors since they are not probability densities.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The only relevance they have is found in the corresponding posterior, as long as it is well-defined for all observations.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] By contrast, likelihood functions do not need to be integrated, and a likelihood function that is uniformly 1 corresponds to the absence of data (all models are equally likely, given no data): Bayes' rule multiplies a prior by the likelihood, and an empty product is just the constant likelihood 1.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] However, without starting with a prior probability distribution, one does not end up getting a posterior probability distribution, and thus cannot integrate or compute expected values or loss.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] See Likelihood function § Non-integrability for details.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] These functions, interpreted as uniform distributions, can also be interpreted as the likelihood function in the absence of data, but are not proper priors.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] While in Bayesian statistics the prior probability is used to represent initial beliefs about an uncertain parameter, in statistical mechanics the a priori probability is used to describe the initial state of a system.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The classical version is defined as the ratio of the number of elementary events (e.g., the number of times a die is thrown) to the total number of events—and these considered purely deductively, i.e., without any experimenting.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In the case of the die if we look at it on the table without throwing it, each elementary event is reasoned deductively to have the same probability—thus the probability of each outcome of an imaginary throwing of the (perfect) die or simply by counting the number of faces is 1/6.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Each face of the die appears with equal probability—probability being a measure defined for each elementary event.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The result is different if we throw the die twenty times and ask how many times (out of 20) the number 6 appears on the upper face.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In this case time comes into play and we have a different type of probability depending on time or the number of times the die is thrown.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] On the other hand, the a priori probability is independent of time—you can look at the die on the table as long as you like without touching it and you deduce the probability for the number 6 to appear on the upper face is 1/6.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In statistical mechanics, e.g., that of a gas contained in a finite volume V , both the spatial coordinates $q_{i}$ and the momentum coordinates $p_{i}$ of the individual gas elements (atoms or molecules) are finite in the phase space spanned by these coordinates.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In 1 dimension (length L ) this number or statistical weight or a priori weighting is $L\Delta p/h$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In customary 3 dimensions (volume V ) the corresponding number can be calculated to be $V4\pi p^{2}\Delta p/h^{3}$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In order to understand this quantity as giving a number of states in quantum (i.e., wave) mechanics, recall that in quantum mechanics every particle is associated with a matter wave which is the solution of a Schrödinger equation.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In the case of free particles (of energy $\epsilon ={\bf {p}}^{2}/2m$ ) like those of a gas in a box of volume $V=L^{3}$ such a matter wave is explicitly $\psi \propto \sin {\frac {l\pi x}{L}}\sin {\frac {m\pi y}{L}}\sin {\frac {n\pi z}{L}},$ where $l,m,n$ are integers.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The number of different $(l,m,n)$ values and hence states in the region between $p,p+dp,p^{2}={\bf {p}}^{2},$ is then found to be the above expression $V4\pi p^{2}dp/h^{3}$ by considering the area covered by these points.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Moreover, in view of the uncertainty relation, which in 1 spatial dimension is $\Delta q\Delta p\geq h,$ these states are indistinguishable (i.e., these states do not carry labels).
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] An important consequence is a result known as Liouville's theorem, i.e., the time independence of this phase space volume element and thus of the a priori probability.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] A time dependence of this quantity would imply known information about the dynamics of the system, and hence would not be an a priori probability.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Thus the region ${\displaystyle \Omega$ when differentiated with respect to time t yields zero (with the help of Hamilton's equations): The volume at time t is the same as at time zero.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] One describes this also as conservation of information.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In the full quantum theory one has an analogous conservation law.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In this case, the phase space region is replaced by a subspace of the space of states expressed in terms of a projection operator P , and instead of the probability in phase space, one has the probability density ${\displaystyle \Sigma$ where N is the dimensionality of the subspace.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The conservation law in this case is expressed by the unitarity of the S-matrix.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In either case, the considerations assume a closed isolated system.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] This closed isolated system is a system with (1) a fixed energy E and (2) a fixed number of particles N in (c) a state of equilibrium.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] If one considers a huge number of replicas of this system, one obtains what is called a *microcanonical ensemble*.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] It is for this system that one postulates in quantum statistics the "fundamental postulate of equal a priori probabilities of an isolated system." This says that the isolated system in equilibrium occupies each of its accessible states with the same probability.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] This fundamental postulate therefore allows us to equate the a priori probability to the degeneracy of a system, i.e., to the number of different states with the same energy.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] The following example illustrates the a priori probability (or a priori weighting) in (a) classical and (b) quantal contexts.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] From wave mechanics it is known that the energy levels of a rotating diatomic molecule are given by $E_{n}={\frac {n(n+1)h^{2}}{8\pi ^{2}I}},$ each such level being (2n+1)-fold degenerate.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In the case of the one-dimensional simple harmonic oscillator of natural frequency $\nu$ one finds correspondingly: (a) $\Omega \propto dE/\nu$ , and (b) $\Sigma \propto dn$ (no degeneracy).
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Thus in quantum mechanics the a priori probability is effectively a measure of the degeneracy, i.e. the number of states having the same energy.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In the case of the hydrogen atom or Coulomb potential (where the evaluation of the phase space volume for constant energy is more complicated) one knows that the quantum mechanical degeneracy is $n^{2}$ with $E\propto 1/n^{2}$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Thus in this case $\Sigma \propto n^{2}dn$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] In statistical mechanics, it is common to derive so-called distribution functions f for various statistics.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] An important aspect in the derivation is the taking into account of the indistinguishability of particles and states in quantum statistics, i.e., there particles and states do not have labels.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] On the other hand, the a priori probability $g_{i}$ is a measure of the number of wave mechanical states available.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Above no mention was made of electric or other fields.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] Thus with no such fields present we have the Fermi-Dirac distribution as above.
[src:bayesian-inference/prior-probability] But with such fields present we have this additional dependence of f .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] To derive a lower bound for the marginal likelihood (sometimes called the *evidence*) of the observed data (i.e. the marginal probability of the data given the model, with marginalization performed over unobserved variables).
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This is typically used for performing model selection, the general idea being that a higher marginal likelihood for a given model indicates a better fit of the data by that model and hence a greater probability that the model in question was the one that generated the data.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In particular, whereas Monte Carlo techniques provide a numerical approximation to the exact posterior using a set of samples, variational Bayes provides a locally-optimal, exact analytical solution to an approximation of the posterior.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] As in EM, it finds a set of optimal parameter values, and it has the same alternating structure as does EM, based on a set of interlocked (mutually dependent) equations that cannot be solved analytically.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] For many applications, variational Bayes produces solutions of comparable accuracy to Gibbs sampling at greater speed.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] However, deriving the set of equations used to update the parameters iteratively often requires a large amount of work compared with deriving the comparable Gibbs sampling equations.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This is the case even for many models that are conceptually quite simple, as is demonstrated below in the case of a basic non-hierarchical model with only two parameters and no latent variables.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The similarity (or dissimilarity) is measured in terms of a dissimilarity function $d(Q;P)$ and hence inference is performed by selecting the distribution $Q(\mathbf {Z} )$ that minimizes $d(Q;P)$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The most common type of variational Bayes uses the Kullback–Leibler divergence (KL-divergence) of *Q* from *P* as the choice of dissimilarity function.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This choice makes this minimization tractable.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Note that *Q* and *P* are reversed from what one might expect.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This use of reversed KL-divergence is conceptually similar to the expectation–maximization algorithm.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The marginalization over $\mathbf {Z}$ to calculate $P(\mathbf {X} )$ in the denominator is typically intractable, because, for example, the search space of $\mathbf {Z}$ is combinatorially large.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Therefore, we seek an approximation, using $Q(\mathbf {Z} )\approx P(\mathbf {Z} \mid \mathbf {X} )$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] As the *log-evidence* $\log P(\mathbf {X} )$ is fixed with respect to Q , maximizing the final term ${\mathcal {L}}(Q)$ minimizes the KL divergence of Q from P .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] By appropriate choice of Q , ${\mathcal {L}}(Q)$ becomes tractable to compute and to maximize.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Hence we have both an analytical approximation Q for the posterior $P(\mathbf {Z} \mid \mathbf {X} )$ , and a lower bound ${\mathcal {L}}(Q)$ for the log-evidence $\log P(\mathbf {X} )$ (since the KL-divergence is non-negative).
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The lower bound ${\mathcal {L}}(Q)$ is known as the (negative) **variational free energy** in analogy with thermodynamic free energy because it can also be expressed as a negative energy $\operatorname {E} _{Q}[\log P(\mathbf {Z} ,\mathbf {X} )]$ plus the entropy of Q .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The term ${\mathcal {L}}(Q)$ is also known as **Evidence Lower Bound**, abbreviated as **ELBO**, to emphasize that it is a lower (worst-case) bound on the log-evidence of the data.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The term $\zeta (\mathbf {X} )$ is often called the evidence lower bound (**ELBO**) in practice, since $P(\mathbf {X} )\geq \zeta (\mathbf {X} )=\exp({\mathcal {L}}(Q^{*}))$ , as shown above.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] By interchanging the roles of $\mathbf {Z} _{1}$ and $\mathbf {Z} _{2},$ we can iteratively compute the approximated $q^{*}(\mathbf {Z} _{1})$ and $q^{*}(\mathbf {Z} _{2})$ of the true model's marginals $P(\mathbf {Z} _{1}\mid \mathbf {X} )$ and $P(\mathbf {Z} _{2}\mid \mathbf {X} ),$ respectively.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Although this iterative scheme is guaranteed to converge monotonically, the converged $Q^{*}$ is only a local minimizer of $D_{\mathrm {KL} }(Q\parallel P)$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The constant in the above expression is related to the normalizing constant (the denominator in the expression above for $q_{j}^{*}$ ) and is usually reinstated by inspection, as the rest of the expression can usually be recognized as being a known type of distribution (e.g.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This creates circular dependencies between the parameters of the distributions over variables in one partition and the expectations of variables in the other partitions.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] An algorithm of this sort is guaranteed to converge.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The formula for the distribution's parameters will be expressed in terms of the prior distributions' hyperparameters (which are known constants), but also in terms of expectations of functions of variables in other partitions.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Usually these expectations can be simplified into functions of expectations of the variables themselves (i.e. the means); sometimes expectations of squared variables (which can be related to the variance of the variables), or expectations of higher powers (i.e. higher moments) also appear.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In most cases, the other variables' distributions will be from known families, and the formulas for the relevant expectations can be looked up.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] However, those formulas depend on those distributions' parameters, which depend in turn on the expectations about other variables.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The result is that the formulas for the parameters of each variable's distributions can be expressed as a series of equations with mutual, nonlinear dependencies among the variables.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Usually, it is not possible to solve this system of equations directly.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] However, as described above, the dependencies suggest a simple iterative algorithm, which in most cases is guaranteed to converge.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] An example will make this process clearer.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The following theorem is referred to as a duality formula for variational inference.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] It explains some important properties of the variational distributions used in variational Bayes methods.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Theorem Consider two probability spaces $(\Theta ,{\mathcal {F}},P)$ and $(\Theta ,{\mathcal {F}},Q)$ with $Q\ll P$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Assume that there is a common dominating probability measure $\lambda$ such that $P\ll \lambda$ and $Q\ll \lambda$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Let h denote any real-valued random variable on $(\Theta ,{\mathcal {F}},P)$ that satisfies $\exp h\in L_{1}(P)$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] almost surely with respect to probability measure Q , where $p(\theta )=dP/d\lambda$ and $q(\theta )=dQ/d\lambda$ denote the Radon–Nikodym derivatives of the probability measures P and Q with respect to $\lambda$ , respectively.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Consider a simple non-hierarchical Bayesian model consisting of a set of i.i.d. observations from a Gaussian distribution, with unknown mean and variance.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In the following, we work through this model in great detail to illustrate the workings of the variational Bayes method.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] For mathematical convenience, in the following example we work in terms of the precision — i.e. the reciprocal of the variance (or in a multivariate Gaussian, the inverse of the covariance matrix) — rather than the variance itself.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] We place conjugate prior distributions on the unknown mean $\mu$ and precision $\tau$ , i.e. the mean also follows a Gaussian distribution while the precision follows a gamma distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The hyperparameters $\mu _{0},\lambda _{0},a_{0}$ and $b_{0}$ in the prior distributions are fixed, given values.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] They can be set to small positive numbers to give broad prior distributions indicating ignorance about the prior distributions of $\mu$ and $\tau$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Assume that $q(\mu ,\tau )=q(\mu )q(\tau )$ , i.e. that the posterior distribution factorizes into independent factors for $\mu$ and $\tau$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This type of assumption underlies the variational Bayesian method.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The true posterior distribution does not in fact factor this way (in fact, in this simple case, it is known to be a Gaussian-gamma distribution), and hence the result we obtain will be an approximation.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In the above derivation, C , $C_{2}$ and $C_{3}$ refer to values that are constant with respect to $\mu$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Note that the term $\operatorname {E} _{\tau }[\ln p(\tau )]$ is not a function of $\mu$ and will have the same value regardless of the value of $\mu$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Hence in line 3 we can absorb it into the constant term at the end.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The last line is simply a quadratic polynomial in $\mu$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Since this is the logarithm of $q_{\mu }^{*}(\mu )$ , we can see that $q_{\mu }^{*}(\mu )$ itself is a Gaussian distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Note that all of the above steps can be shortened by using the formula for the sum of two quadratics.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The derivation of $q_{\tau }^{*}(\tau )$ is similar to above, although we omit some of the details for the sake of brevity.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Exponentiating both sides, we can see that $q_{\tau }^{*}(\tau )$ is a gamma distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In each case, the parameters for the distribution over one of the variables depend on expectations taken with respect to the other variable.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Note that there are circular dependencies among the formulas for $\lambda _{N}$ and $b_{N}$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Initialize $\lambda _{N}$ to some arbitrary value.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Use the current value of $\lambda _{N},$ along with the known values of the other parameters, to compute $b_{N}$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Use the current value of $b_{N},$ along with the known values of the other parameters, to compute $\lambda _{N}$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Repeat the last two steps until convergence (i.e. until neither value has changed more than some small amount).
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] It can be shown that this algorithm is guaranteed to converge to a local maximum.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Note also that the posterior distributions have the same form as the corresponding prior distributions.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] We did *not* assume this; the only assumption we made was that the distributions factorize, and the form of the distributions followed naturally.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] It turns out (see below) that the fact that the posterior distributions have the same form as the prior distributions is not a coincidence, but a general result whenever the prior distributions are members of the exponential family, which is the case for most of the standard distributions.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Partition the unobserved variables into two or more subsets, over which the independent factors will be derived.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] There is no universal procedure for doing this; creating too many subsets yields a poor approximation, while creating too few makes the entire variational Bayes procedure intractable.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Typically, the first split is to separate the parameters and latent variables; often, this is enough by itself to produce a tractable result.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Assume that the partitions are called $\mathbf {Z} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {Z} _{M}$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Fill in the formula for the joint probability distribution using the graphical model.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Any component conditional distributions that don't involve any of the variables in $\mathbf {Z} _{j}$ can be ignored; they will be folded into the constant term.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Simplify the formula and apply the expectation operator, following the above example.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Ideally, this should simplify into expectations of basic functions of variables not in $\mathbf {Z} _{j}$ (e.g. first or second raw moments, expectation of a logarithm, etc.).
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In order for the variational Bayes procedure to work well, these expectations should generally be expressible analytically as functions of the parameters and/or hyperparameters of the distributions of these variables.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In all cases, these expectation terms are constants with respect to the variables in the current partition.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The functional form of the formula with respect to the variables in the current partition indicates the type of distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In particular, exponentiating the formula generates the probability density function (PDF) of the distribution (or at least, something proportional to it, with unknown normalization constant).
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In order for the overall method to be tractable, it should be possible to recognize the functional form as belonging to a known distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Significant mathematical manipulation may be required to convert the formula into a form that matches the PDF of a known distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] When this can be done, the normalization constant can be reinstated by definition, and equations for the parameters of the known distribution can be derived by extracting the appropriate parts of the formula.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] When this procedure can be applied to all partitions, the result is a set of mutually linked equations specifying the optimum values of all parameters.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] An expectation–maximization (EM) type procedure is then applied, picking an initial value for each parameter and the iterating through a series of steps, where at each step we cycle through the equations, updating each parameter in turn.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Due to all of the mathematical manipulations involved, it is easy to lose track of the big picture.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] "Analytical approximation" means that a formula can be written down for the posterior distribution.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The formula generally consists of a product of well-known probability distributions, each of which *factorizes* over a set of unobserved variables (i.e. it is conditionally independent of the other variables, given the observed data).
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This formula is not the true posterior distribution, but an approximation to it; in particular, it will generally agree fairly closely in the lowest moments of the unobserved variables, e.g. the mean and variance.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The result of all of the mathematical manipulations is (1) the identity of the probability distributions making up the factors, and (2) mutually dependent formulas for the parameters of these distributions.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The actual values of these parameters are computed numerically, through an alternating iterative procedure much like EM.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Variational Bayes (VB) is often compared with expectation–maximization (EM).
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The actual numerical procedure is quite similar, in that both are alternating iterative procedures that successively converge on optimum parameter values.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The initial steps to derive the respective procedures are also vaguely similar, both starting out with formulas for probability densities and both involving significant amounts of mathematical manipulations.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] However, there are a number of differences.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Most important is *what* is being computed.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] In other words, $q^{*}(\mathbf {Z} )$ is a product of single-observation multinomial distributions, and factors over each individual $\mathbf {z} _{n}$ , which is distributed as a single-observation multinomial distribution with parameters $r_{nk}$ for $k=1\dots K$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] which is a standard result for categorical distributions.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] These can be converted from proportional to absolute values by normalizing over k so that the corresponding values sum to 1.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] The update equations for the parameters $\alpha _{1\dots K}$ of the variable $\mathbf {\pi }$ depend on the statistic $N_{k}$ , which depends in turn on $r_{nk}$ .
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] An M-step that uses the new value of $r_{nk}$ to compute new values of all the other parameters.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] Note that these steps correspond closely with the standard EM algorithm to derive a maximum likelihood or maximum a posteriori (MAP) solution for the parameters of a Gaussian mixture model.
[src:bayesian-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] This is a general result that holds true for all prior distributions derived from the exponential family.
